signature_matches.name: check mutex
signature_matches.description: host-interaction/mutex
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: check mutex
    namespace: host-interaction/mutex
    authors:
      - moritz.raabe@mandiant.com
      - anushka.virgaonkar@mandiant.com
    scope: basic block
    mbc:
      - Process::Check Mutex [C0043]
    examples:
      - Practical Malware Analysis Lab 01-01.dll_:0x10001010
  features:
    - and:
      - or:
        - api: kernel32.OpenMutex
        - match: create mutex
        - api: System.Threading.Mutex::OpenExisting
        - api: System.Threading.Mutex::TryOpenExisting
      - optional:
        - or:
          - api: kernel32.GetLastError
          - number: 2 = ERROR_FILE_NOT_FOUND
          - number: 0xB7 = ERROR_ALREADY_EXISTS

signature_matches.name: get OS version
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: get OS version
    authors:
      - "@mr-tz"
    lib: true
    scope: function
    examples:
      - 493167E85E45363D09495D0841C30648:0x401000
      - 5f66b82558ca92e54e77f216ef4c066c:0x44580A
  features:
    - or:
      - api: RtlGetVersion
      - api: ntoskrnl.PsGetVersion
      - api: GetVersion
      - api: GetVersionEx
      - api: VerifyVersionInfo
      - api: VerSetConditionMask
      - api: RtlGetNtVersionNumbers
      - api: GetProductInfo
      - and:
        - match: PEB access
        - or:
          - and:
            - arch: i386
            - or:
              - offset: 0xA4 = PEB->OSMajorVersion
              - offset: 0xA8 = PEB->OSMinorVersion
              - offset: 0xAC = PEB->OSBuildNumber
          - and:
            - arch: amd64
            - or:
              - offset: 0x118 = PEB->OSMajorVersion
              - offset: 0x11C = PEB->OSMinorVersion
              - offset: 0x120 = PEB->OSBuildNumber

signature_matches.name: link many functions at runtime
signature_matches.description: linking/runtime-linking
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: link many functions at runtime
    namespace: linking/runtime-linking
    authors:
      - moritz.raabe@mandiant.com
      - joakim@intezer.com
    scope: function
    att&ck:
      - Execution::Shared Modules [T1129]
    examples:
      - b7b5e1253710d8927cbe07d52d2d2e10:0x401000
  features:
    - or:
      - and:
        - os: windows
        - match: link function at runtime on Windows
        - or:
          - count(api(kernel32.GetProcAddress)): 5 or more
          - count(api(ntdll.LdrGetProcedureAddress)): 5 or more
      - and:
        - os: linux
        - match: link function at runtime on Linux
        - or:
          - count(api(dlsym)): 5 or more
          - count(api(dlvsym)): 5 or more

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Regsvr32 DLL Execution With Uncommon Extension
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects a "regsvr32" execution where the DLL doesn't contain a common file extension.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Files With System Process Name In Unsuspected Locations
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the creation of an executable with a system process name in folders other than the system ones (System32, SysWOW64, etc.).
It is highly recommended to perform an initial baseline before using this rule in production.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Sander Wiebing, Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the execution of a Windows system binary that is usually located in the system folder from an uncommon location.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Patrick Bareiss, Anton Kutepov, oscd.community, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects suspicious parent processes that should not have any children or should only have a single possible child program
Identifies use of Fodhelper.exe to bypass User Account Control. Adversaries use this technique to execute privileged processes.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: E.M. Anhaus (originally from Atomic Blue Detections, Tony Lambert), oscd.community

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Bad Opsec Defaults Sacrificial Processes With Improper Arguments
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects attackers using tooling with bad opsec defaults.
E.g. spawning a sacrificial process to inject a capability into the process without taking into account how the process is normally run.
One trivial example of this is using rundll32.exe without arguments as a sacrificial process (default in CS, now highlighted by c2lint), running WerFault without arguments (Kraken - credit am0nsec), and other examples.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Oleg Kolesnikov @securonix invrep_de, oscd.community, Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Christian Burkard (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the shell open key manipulation (exefile and ms-settings) used for persistence and the pattern of UAC Bypass using fodhelper.exe, computerdefaults.exe, slui.exe via registry keys (e.g. UACMe 33 or 62)
Bypasses User Account Control using a fileless method
Detects process creation events that use the Sysnative folder (common for CobaltStrike spawns)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Python Image Load By Non-Python Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the image load of "Python Core" by a non-Python process. This might be indicative of a Python script bundled with Py2Exe.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Patrick St. John, OTR (Open Threat Research)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Regsvr32 Execution From Potential Suspicious Location
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects execution of regsvr32 where the DLL is located in a potentially suspicious location.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Hidden Executable In NTFS Alternate Data Stream
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the creation of an ADS (Alternate Data Stream) that contains an executable by looking at a non-empty Imphash

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Unsigned DLL Loaded by Windows Utility
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects windows utilities loading an unsigned or untrusted DLL.
Adversaries often abuse those programs to proxy execution of malicious code.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Removal of Potential COM Hijacking Registry Keys
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects any deletion of entries in ".*\shell\open\command" registry keys.
These registry keys might have been used for COM hijacking activities by a threat actor or an attacker and the deletion could indicate steps to remove its tracks.
Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Files With System Process Name In Unsuspected Locations
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the creation of an executable with a system process name in folders other than the system ones (System32, SysWOW64, etc.).
It is highly recommended to perform an initial baseline before using this rule in production.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Sander Wiebing, Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects non-interactive PowerShell activity by looking at the "powershell" process with a non-user GUI process such as "explorer.exe" as a parent.
